âœ… 1. Common Problems in Database Design
Null values: Waste storage, unclear meaning.

Redundancy: Repetition leads to inconsistency.

Repeated columns: Violate atomicity.

Update anomalies: Changes must be made in multiple places.

â¡ These problems can be solved by decomposition using functional dependencies.

âœ… 2. Functional Dependency (FD)
A functional dependency (FD) is a constraint between two sets of attributes.

Denoted as: X -> Y (Y is functionally dependent on X)

X is called the determinant.

Example:

nginx
Copy
Edit
Emp_ID â†’ Emp_Name
Given the same Emp_ID, the Emp_Name must also be the same.

âœ… 3. Types of Functional Dependencies

Type	Description	Example
Full FD	Y depends on the whole of X (composite key).	Roll_No, Subject â†’ Marks
Partial FD	Y depends on part of a composite key.	Roll_No â†’ Student_Name
Transitive FD	X â†’ Y and Y â†’ Z implies X â†’ Z	Roll â†’ Marks â†’ Grade
Multivalued FD	X determines multiple values of Y.	Course_ID â†’â†’ Topics
Trivial FD	Y is a subset of X.	A, B â†’ B
âœ… 4. Armstrongâ€™s Axioms (Inference Rules)
Reflexivity: If Y âŠ† X, then X â†’ Y

Augmentation: If X â†’ Y, then XZ â†’ YZ

Transitivity: If X â†’ Y and Y â†’ Z, then X â†’ Z

Additivity (Union): X â†’ Y and X â†’ Z â‡’ X â†’ YZ

Decomposition: X â†’ YZ â‡’ X â†’ Y and X â†’ Z

Pseudotransitivity: If X â†’ Y and YZ â†’ W, then XZ â†’ W

âœ… 5. Attribute Closure (Xâº)
Used to find all attributes that can be functionally derived from X.

Steps:

Start with Xâº = X

Apply FDs where LHS âŠ† Xâº

Add RHS to Xâº

Repeat until stable

